Create a program that declares an array of size 5.

Intentionally access an invalid index (e.g., list[5]).

Observe and record what happens when you run the program.

Modify your code to prevent accessing invalid indices.

Explain why C++ does not automatically check array bounds.


Reflection:
How can array index errors cause unpredictable results?

What are good programming practices to prevent them?

_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    // Declare an array of size 5
    int list[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

    std::cout << list[5] << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

It output a numbers 779647075

 _____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________


#include <iostream>

int main() {
   // Declare an array of size 5
    int list[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

    // Loop through the array, but stop before potentially accessing an invalid index
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {
        std::cout << "list[" << i << "] = " << list[i] << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}















